<DOCNO> AP890219-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-89 2341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BankBoard-Martin     02-19 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bank Board-Martin,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Interpretation Could Let Official Keep Stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government agency regulating the savings
and loan industry has relaxed its reading of an internal rule in a
way that apparently will allow one of its top officials to keep his
stock in a family business.
   The rule, which had prompted Federal Home Loan Bank Board member
Roger Martin to promise to get rid of the stock, has been
interpreted too literally, according to Harry W. Quillian, deputy
general counsel for the board.
   Martin promised when he joined the board in 1987 that he would
divest himself of his 29 percent interest in Pope Scientific Inc.
That promise was made to the Office of Government Ethics and
incorporated into Martin's sworn testimony during his Senate
confirmation hearing.
   Once he made that promise, federal ethics laws required Martin to
carry through and rid himself of the stock within 90 days of his
confirmation. But he says he did not want to dispose of his holding
in the company and, after making his promise, received verbal advice
that he could keep the stock.
   Quillian wrote to Martin last week saying that the interpretation
of the agency's rules he gave Martin in 1987 was wrong.
   The original interpretation resulted from defining the word
``employee'' in the board regulation so broadly that it would, in
effect, consider a company in which an employee owned a substantial
interest an ``employee'' of the board as well as the actual employee
himself.
   That way, rules on such things as conflicts of interest and
ethics would apply not only to board employees, but to the actions
of companies in which they held a substantial interest.
   ``While that is certainly the literal interpretation of that
provision, such an interpretation would of course be
unenforceable,'' Quillian wrote to Martin last week. ``Accordingly,
we have decided after further research and reflection that the
definition cannot and should not be interpreted literally.''
   Pope Scientific, based in Menomonee Falls, Wis., manufactures
laboratory glassware and instruments. While it has done work for the
government from time to time, it would have little or no occasion to
bring it into contact with the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
   In letters to The Milwaukee Sentinel and USA Today, Martin
complained that under the literal interpretation of the board's
rules, ``I would have had to report on federal financial disclosure
forms the entire interest of Pope as if I were its sole owner.''
   Until Martin became a member of the bank board in 1987, he was
Pope Scientific's chairman. His wife, Ann, owns 51 percent of the
company and is its president. His son, Geoffrey, is vice president.
   Martin also said that ``there is no such requirement'' that would
compel him to sell his interest in the company.
   However, Gary Davis, chief counsel for the Office of Government
Ethics, said that once Martin made a promise to divest, he either
had to do it or explain why not.
   ``He has a requirement to act on the terms of his ethics
agreement unless he provides an explanation for the change in
conditions,'' Davis said.
   Using the range categories on financial disclosure forms, Martin
listed his 29 percent stake in the company as being worth between
$100,000 and $250,000.
   Martin did sell other financial holdings when he joined the bank
board. He had held stock in MGIC Investment Corp. and was vice
president of Mortgage Guaranty Insurance Corp. He sold that stock,
resigned the post and promised not to take part in matters affecting
that company or the mortgage insurance industry.
   The bank board, which regulates and audits the nation's savings
and loans, has been overrun with work as that industry has sunk into
such deep financial trouble that President Bush has proposed a
massive federal bailout.
   Some of the board's paperwork has fallen through the cracks.
   ``For the last any number of months we've been like one-armed
paper hangers,'' Quillian said.
   ``But in the present circumstances it seemed like it was well to
drop everything and get this out on paper, which we've now done,''
Quillian said.
   Asked what the ``present circumstances'' were, he replied: ``You
guys writing about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
