<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-89 2343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Niger-Food     02-19 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Niger-Food,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rains Bring Plentiful Harvest, But Highlight Deeper Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRNI N'GAOURE, Niger (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kadi Umarou emerged from a
helmet-shaped granary of golden straw, her arms laden with millet
stalks, and headed home past a dozen other new granaries built for
the best harvest in 20 years.
   This country on the southern edge of the Sahara Desert, which has
been forced to ask the world for food repeatedly for more than a
decade, is feeding itself this year.
   Rains last spring and summer were plentiful and farmers say
conditions for planting hadn't been better in 30 years. The
government reported a grain surplus of more than 200,000 tons after
the harvest last fall, enough to carry the country through this
spring's planting.
   Pastures are green and herds are increasing. Bellies are full and
children are smiling. Things are as good as they have been in a
long, long time.
   ``My children eat now when they want. My husband is strong. I am
less afraid and still there is more grain,'' Mrs. Umarou said,
speaking in the tribal language of Djerma through a translator.
   But in a region where problems are profound, a year as good as
1988 shows just how bad things really are.
   Ernest Gibson, an official with the U.S. Agency for International
Development in Niamey, about 20 miles away, said bumper harvests in
this West African nation are so rare some villagers didn't know what
to do.
   ``In one village, they have gone a whole generation without
anything left over so they didn't know how to construct granaries.
The government sent a team to teach them,'' Gibson said.
   From Mauritania on the Atlantic coast across to Ethiopia in the
east the situation was much the same, with the countries on the vast
arid border south of the Sahara reporting better than average
rainfall in 1988. Record harvests were reported in Burkina Faso,
Chad and Mali.
   ``If it rained for 20 years you would have healthy people in
Niger,'' said Gibson. ``But you have to turn that abundance into
productive, sustainable, non-agricultural activities. If not, when
the rain stops in the 21st year you will need emergency food.''
   Many experts in development agencies say wealthy people here tend
to invest their money abroad. Exceptions are those who build houses
in the capital to rent and others who buy agricultural products and
horde them for resale.
   ``There is a surplus of millet, prices have fallen and there is
no government price support,'' said Olav Bakken Jensen of CARE.
``The rich merchants buy it, hold it until there isn't any food and
then resell it, often to aid agencies at inflated prices, who
distribute it as emergency food. They can't go wrong and the poor
farmer who needs the cash has no choice but to sell.''
   Even one obvious benefit of the good harvest, well-fed
youngsters, has a sobering side.
   ``Of course the children born this year will get a better
start,'' said Jensen. ``But then there will be more babies, more
marriages by people who have been putting off getting married for
years. Even the government has informally asked people to not use
their extra income to buy too many wives. But this is precisely what
is happening.''
   In the eastern province of Zinder, Mike Edwards of Tulane
University's School of Public Health has been weighing babies in a
project for CARE. He has found some surprising results: the number
of children suffering acute malnutrition has decreased since the
famine of 1984, but the number of children with chronic malnutrition
is on the rise.
   Those who were starved as infants have not yet recovered, he
said, and malnutrition is tied to more than simply how much a child
eats.
   ``Millet is good and children this year are getting lots of
millet. But they are not getting the variety of protein and vitamins
babies need for muscle growth. A baby needs quality, not just
quantity,'' Edwards explained.
   Still, any respite in the harsh environment can't help but boost
morale.
   ``In the first year or two of drought a person can retain some
hope,'' said Horacio Soares, director of the agricultural weather
station set up to monitor conditions after the disastrous 1072-73
drought.
   ``But after years and years, you just give up. With rain, people
feel happier, they're willing to cooperate with government programs
and even push for more help with development.''
</TEXT>
