<FIRST>r a PM-Networks-Japan     02-19 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Networks-Japan,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS Blitzes Other Networks With Massive Far East Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS is blitzing the other networks' coverage of
Emperor Hirohito's funeral and President Bush's trip to the Far East
this week, taking most of its news broadcasts to Japan at a cost of
at least $2 million.
   ABC, NBC and CNN also will be on location for Hirohito's funeral.
Bush will attend the funeral Thursday in Tokyo, then he goes to
China and Korea.
   At a news conference last week, ``Evening News'' anchor Dan
Rather called the coverage ``unprecedented'' by broadcast news, but
warranted by Hirohito's death as a symbol of ``the end of the
postwar era.''
   ABC's Peter Jennings will anchor ``ABC World News Tonight'' from
Tokyo all week. NBC's Tom Brokaw will anchor ``NBC Nightly News''
from Tokyo on Thursday and Friday, then from Beijing on Saturday and
Sunday. CNN's Bernard Shaw and Mary Alice Williams will anchor live
coverage of the funeral from Tokyo.
   The networks have all focused on Japan's culture and economy in
reports leading up to the funeral and Bush's trip.
   CBS, which began on-location coverage Sunday with ``CBS Sunday
Morning,'' also is taking the ``CBS Evening News,'' ``CBS This
Morning,'' ``48 Hours'' and ``Face the Nation'' to Japan. The
coverage concludes next Sunday with ``Face the Nation'' from Beijing.
   The broadcasts will focus on Japan's relationship to the United
States in terms of economy, lifestyles and military interdependence.
   CBS' ``48 Hours'' will have live coverage of the beginning of the
funeral Thursday night, when it will be Friday morning in Japan.
   CBS News figures it will have 18 hours of special coverage from
the Far East at a cost of at least $2 million, Rather said.
   ``We thought long and hard about whether should make this kind of
commitment to this story at this time,'' he said. ``This is a gamble
for us.''
   ``But we think in this particular case we can make it work,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
