<FIRST>r a PM-RepublicanRomance     02-19 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Republican Romance,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Governor and Congresswoman, Politics is Path to Marriage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They met in the Maine Legislature on the
Republican side of the aisle, the raven-haired representative from
Auburn seated directly behind the handsome young floor leader from
Bangor.
   When she decided to run for Congress in 1978, they got together
to map out campaign strategy. Over the years their shared interest
in politics blossomed into something more.
   The decade-long courtship between Rep. Olympia Snowe and Gov.
John R. McKernan will culminate this week in an exchange of marriage
vows.
   ``What holds our relationship together is the fact that we love
politics,'' said Snowe, now in her sixth term in Congress. ``For
some, that becomes a dividing factor, but in our case that obviously
hasn't been the situation.''
   ``We both have our own careers and they happen to be in the same
field,'' said McKernan, a former two-term congressman who was
elected governor in 1986. ``We understand the pressures that are on
each other.''
   The wedding Friday at the Greek Orthodox Church of the Holy
Trinity in Lewiston _ Snowe is of Greek descent _ will begin the
second marriage for both.
   The announcement of their pending nuptials three weeks ago evoked
surprise that two of a small state's most prominent political
figures could have kept a romance of nearly a decade relatively
private.
   ``A hush-hush affair,'' marveled one of Snowe's constituents,
Frances Boisvert of Lewiston. ``Nobody seemed to know anything about
it. But it's nice.''
   Snowe, who turns 42 on Tuesday, was widowed in 1973 when her
husband was killed in an accident while driving home from the
Legislature, where he served in the House. She entered politics by
running successfully for his seat.
   The 40-year-old McKernan's first marriage ended in divorce in
1978. He has an 18-year-old son, Peter.
   McKernan and Snowe realize they will spend most of their time 600
miles apart, one in Washington, the other in the state capital of
Augusta, getting together on weekends and during congressional
recesses.
   They will try, as much as possible, to coordinate their schedules
and expect to divide their time between the Blaine House _ the
executive mansion in Augusta _ and Snowe's home in Auburn, 35 miles
away.
   ``The most important factor in any relationship is
communication,'' Snowe said, describing their daily telephone
conversations. ``Talking about what happens during the day to each
of us makes it feel we're not that far away.''
   Snowe and McKernan said they believe their careers will insulate
them from the problems of other politicians whose marriages broke
because they were unable to balance their political responsibilities
with the demands of family life.
   In other marriages, McKernan noted, ``only one of them is
involved in politics, and the other one gets left behind a lot.''
   They acknowledge their differences in personality. He is
deliberate, an outgrowth of his legal training; she tends to rely
more heavily on instinct.
   The romance blossomed while the two were in Washington, serving
as Maine's delegation in the House. Their private joke on their
trips home: ``Your district or mine?''
   The relationship was never splashed across the front pages, but
neither was it concealed. Whenever the subject was broached by
reporters, Snowe and McKernan acknowledged that they dated each
other but offered no elaboration.
   The reaction to their engagement has been positive, they said,
with congratulatory calls from President and Barbara Bush and
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis. Referring to his and Snowe's
shared ethnic background, Dukakis told McKernan that ``mixed
marriages work _ especially if one of the partners is Greek.''
McKernan is a Protestant.
   Their honeymoon will be a weekend in New York with dinner and the
theater. Both must be in Washington the following week, Snowe to
tend to her congressional duties and McKernan for a meeting of the
nation's governors.
   While the wedding itself will be limited to family members and
close friends, the couple mailed invitations to 7,500 friends and
political supporters for a reception the following week at the
Augusta Civic Center.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
