<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-Elections     02-19 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Elections,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Coalition Kicks Off Presidential Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major opposition candidate on
Saturday kicked off his presidential campaign and promised improved
social and political rights for women.
   ``The beginning has begun toward a better Panama, of light,
fraternity, peace and abundance, where democracy, justice and
liberty exists,'' said Guillermo Endara, presidential candidate for
the Democratic Civilian Opposition Alliance.
   Endara, a 52-year-old attorney, spoke Saturday at a women's
convention organized by opposition party members. Presidential
elections are scheduled for May 7.
   Endara promised to improve the rights of Panamanian women. He
said that to beat the government-backed coalition in the election,
he would follow a program of ``democratic convictions and social
justice.''
   The government-supported National Liberation Coalition candidate
is Carlos Duque. Also running for the presidency is Hildebrando
Nicosia of the Authentic Panamanian Party.
   Endara previously was spokesman for Arias Madrid, a three-time
Panamanian president who ran three more times and lost. During two
of the unsuccessful bids, Madrid claimed victory was stolen from him
by election fraud.
   The opposition wants to use the elections to oust Panama's de
facto ruler, army commander Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Noriega is not a candidate in the presidential elections.
   Noriega has been in power since February 1988 when he
orchestrated the ouster of President Eric Arturo Delvalle. Delvalle
had tried to fire Noriega in the wake of his federal indictment in
Florida on drug charges.
</TEXT>
