<FIRST>u a AM-CBSNotWelcome     02-19 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CBS Not Welcome,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Affiliate Says It Won't Let Network News Team Back Next Mardi Gras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A CBS affiliate isn't inviting the network
back to its newsroom next Mardi Gras because the network's report
focused on the city's crime problem and was ``misleading and very
superficial,'' the affiliate's news director said.
   ``Our video files will not be open to CBS, nor will any editing
facilities or satellite equipment be available. Any story you do,
you will do on your own. You won't have our help,'' Joe Duke, news
director of local affiliate WWL, said in a letter to CBS News
President David Burk.
   Duke wrote to protest a report on ``CBS Evening News'' done by
correspondent Peter Van Zant during Mardi Gras earlier this month.
   The report ``began with a brief mention of our Mardi Gras
celebration, and juxtaposed that with a series of murder scenes and
a long discussion of our crime problems,'' Duke wrote.
   Although there has been an increase in murders this year, Duke
said that ``to combine the elements of Mardi Gras and the crime
problem in a very quick piece creates a simplistic, misleading and
very superficial look at our city and in no way reflects what the
community is doing to solve the problem.''
   George Schweitzer, a network spokesman in New York, said Saturday
he was not familiar with the situation and could not comment. He
referred calls to another spokesman, but a message left on his
telephone answering machine wasn't returned.
   New Orleans had almost a slaying a day during January and police
said they found the body of the 34th victim of the year Saturday.
Police have blamed the increase on drugs.
   City Council, which had sent its own letter of complaint to CBS,
commended Duke for his strong protest and asked residents to boycott
CBS programming for two weeks.
   Duke thanked the council but asked viewers to delay the boycott
until after the ratings period in March. Those ratings are used to
set advertising rates.
</TEXT>
