<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines-Military     02-19 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Military,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Offers Peace Talks To Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGUIO, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino told new
officers Sunday to shun coup plots and urged them to crush communist
rebels and other ``enemies of freedom'' who refuse to settle
disputes with her government peacefully.
   ``Those who sapped the strength of this country will ask you to
join them in exploiting its weaknesses,'' Mrs. Aquino told 113
graduating cadets during commencement exercises at the Philippine
Military Academy, 150 miles north of Manila.
   ``Ignore them,'' she ordered. ``Ignore them out of patriotism,
ingore them out of prudence. This country, this government and this
leader have more strength than appearances suggest.''
   Graduates of the nation's only military academy spearheaded the
six armed attempts to topple Mrs. Aquino since she took power in the
February 1986 civilian-military uprising against President Ferdinand
Marcos.
   Troops here and in Manila were placed on maximum alert in advance
of Sunday's commencement because of rumors that right-wing
extremists would launch a new coup attempt.
   Hundreds of troops, some of them flown here from Manila, guarded
strategic points near the mountain-top academy. Bomb-sniffing dogs
checked cadets before the ceremony began under brillantly clear
skies.
   In March 1987, a bomb exploded on the academy parade ground a few
days before the commencement, killing four people and injuring nine
others. Mrs. Aquino said the bomb was intended for her.
   In her speech, Mrs. Aquino told the cadets it was their duty to
protect democratic gains from both communist rebels and right-wing
extremists in their ranks.
   ``Fight them wherever they appear and threaten our people, our
work that we are striving to make of this country,'' she said.
   She challenged the cadets to join with civilian authorities in
healing the nation's wounds and building democracy.
   ``To the enemies of freedom, the armed opponents of our
government on the left and the right, I address these words: Let us
sit down and try to settle our differences by talk,'' she said.
``And if we cannot, by all means, let us do so by arms. But let us
not infect the next generation in civil society and in the armed
forces with narrow causes and hatreds of the past.''
</TEXT>
