<HEAD>Nixon Friends Reportedly Urged To Stonewall TV Version Of `The Final
Days'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide has urged former President Nixon's friends
to stonewall it when producers ask for help in making a television
version of the book ``The Final Days,'' a newspaper reported.
   Nixon reportedly hated the book by Bob Woodward and Carl
Bernstein, which gave a detailed account of the last days in the
Watergate-battered White Hous, and blames it for a stroke suffered
by his wife, Pat.
   In a memo to a few dozen Nixon loyalists, aide John Taylor said
ABC is asking for help on a ``film about the Nixon presidency''
without saying the project is based on ``The Final Days,'' The Miami
Herald reported Saturday.
   ``Because of the singularly odious and vicious nature of this
project, we are asking everyone, in deference to the Nixon family,
to refuse to have anything to do either with this project or indeed
for the time being with ABC,'' Taylor wrote.
   ``It may well be that the producers wish to recruit other of
President Nixon's friends and family and are therefore covering up
the true nature of the project as long as possible,'' the memo says.
``They must be aware of the reaction that they would get from RN
loyalists at the mention of the book's title.''
   Woodward, who is helping with the movie, says there's no cover-up
on the producers' part.
   ``This is the classic enemies-list mentality that led to all the
trouble,'' Woodward said Friday. ``My question to Mr. Taylor is:
Don't they ever learn?''
</TEXT>
