<SECOND>AM-BRF--Britain-Smallpox,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Men Digging Up Old Cemetery Will Get Smallpox Vaccinations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLOUCESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers who plan to excavate an old
hospital cemetery will be given smallpox vaccinations because the
virus, which has been declared eradicated worldwide, could still be
lurking underground.
   The director of the project, Malcolm Atkin, said the workers will
excavate the cemetery adjacent to the city's Old Infirmary hospital
in search of the remains of buildings from the Roman era to the 17th
century.
   The city council's excavation unit wants to explore the burial
ground before it is developed into a parking lot and shopping
center. Aiken said he has asked the developer for a donation to help
pay for the excavation.
   ``We have been advised by the Health and Safety Executive that
smallpox ... germs can stay alive underground indefinitely,'' said
Atkin. ``The site will be completely screened off from the public
during the dig.''
   The World Health Organization declared smallpox eradicated in
1980.
