<FIRST>r a AM-ClownCase     02-19 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clown Case,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sex-Offender Clown Given Probation, Undergoing Self-Punishment Therapy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A professional clown who admitted
trying to pay a teen-age boy to have sex with him has been given
probation with orders that he continue therapy including punishing
himself with ammonia or electric shock to inhibit such urges.
   The sentence given Friday to Marvin Matthow, 56, who works as a
clown at children's parties, was criticized by Deputy District
Attorney Karla Hansen, who sought a prison term because Matthow is a
two-time offender.
   While in prison for a similar sex offense, Hansen said, Matthow
advertised for boys, ostensibly to serve as apprentices, but
actually to use for sex.
   ``I don't think there is any way the court can ensure that young
boys won't be victimized by this defendant again,'' Hansen said
after court recessed.
   District Judge Richard Toth said the five-year probation term was
proper because the therapy Matthow has been undergoing is ``worse
punishment than anything our prison system offers.''
   Since November, when Matthow admitted asking a 17-year-old boy to
engage in sex for money, Matthow has been voluntarily under
treatment at the Behavioral Medicine Institute in Atlanta.
   His treatment includes sniffing ammonia or enduring an electric
shock whenever he has an urge to have sex with an adolescent male.
   At first, the treatment was supervised by the staff. Institute
officials say Matthow has progressed to where he is allowed to
inflict the punishment himself and document the punishment by tape
recording it.
   He is currently an outpatient at the institute, under
surveillance by institute staff who make sure he is acting normally,
institute officials said.
   The technique is widely recognized for treating people who are
attracted sexually to children, said Larry Lanzotti, the Colorado
Springs probation officer who recommended probation for Matthow.
   Atlanta psychiatrist Alfred Messer, who is nationally known for
his work with sex offenders, said of the institute's approach:
``It's OK. It's a good program.''
</TEXT>
