<FIRST>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral-Polls     02-19 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral-Polls,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daley's Lead in Mayoral Race Narrowing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increasing support from black voters has enabled
Mayor Eugene Sawyer to narrow the lead held by his rival in the
mayoral Democratic primary, Richard M. Daley, according to two new
polls.
   A poll conducted for the Chicago Sun-Times and WLS-TV found Daley
leading 50 percent to 38 percent, with 10 percent undecided and the
remaining 2 percent split among two minor candidates.
   Five weeks ago, that poll found Daley, the Cook County state's
attorney, leading 51 percent to 27 percent.
   A poll conducted for the Chicago Tribune and published in Sunday
editions put Daley's lead over Sawyer at 45 percent to 37 percent
among likely voters in the Feb. 28 Democratic primary. Seventeen
percent said they were undecided.
   The Democratic primary historically determines the victor in the
general election in this overwhelmingly Democratic city.
   ``This campaign is winding down and we're moving up,'' Sawyer
said Saturday at a meeting of Operation PUSH with its founder, Jesse
Jackson. ``It's very encouraging.''
   Daley, son of the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, spent part of
Saturday walking through one of his strongholds on the city's
Southwest Side.
   ``I said this is going to a very close election,'' said Daley.
``These people down here react more to shaking-hand appearances than
to polls.''
   The biggest swing by voters in the recent Sun-Times poll compared
with last month's poll was among blacks. Support for Sawyer, who is
black, jumped from 47 percent in January to 77 percent in the most
recent poll. Daley, who is white, was supported by 11 percent of
black voters polled, down from 19 percent five weeks ago.
   At the same time, however, Daley increased his support among
white voters by 5 percent and Hispanics voters by 3 percent,
according to the Sun-Times poll of 1,001 registered voters
questioned Feb. 10-14. The margin of error was plus or minus 4
percentage points.
   The Sun-Times-WLS-TV poll was completed just before the
withdrawal from the race of Alderman Lawrence Bloom, and before
Bloom's endorsement of Sawyer. The newspaper said preliminary
responses of people asked their second choices for mayor showed
Daley and Sawyer could get almost equal numbers of Bloom supporters.
   The Tribune poll found Bloom's black supporters moving to Sawyer
by a 4-to-1 margin and his white backers splitting between Daley and
Sawyer. The poll of 1,017 registered voters likely to cast ballots
was conducted for the Tribune by Market Shares Corp. of Mount
Prospect, and has a margin of error of 3 percentage points.
   The Democratic and Republican nominees will compete in the April
4 general election with Alderman Timothy Evans, who skipped the
primary and is running as a third-party candidate. The endosed GOP
candidate is Dr. Herbert Sohn, a North Side physician.
   The winner of the April election will complete the last two years
of the late Harold Washington's second term. Washington, Chicago's
first black mayor, died of a heart attack in November 1987.
</TEXT>
