<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--MissingDoor     02-19 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Missing Door,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmer Finds Plane's Missing Door In Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farmer and his 13-year-old son found half
of a landing-gear door lost from a Flying Tigers Boeing 747 in their
wheat field.
   Paul Pence, 46, and his son, Chris, were inspecting the wheat
field for frost damage Saturday when they found the door. The wheat
field is about 5 miles east of the runway at Rickenbacker Air
Industrial Park, where a Flying Tigers Boeing 747 landed last
Thursday without a door.
   Officials at the air freight company based in Columbus said the
other half of the double door, which conceals the landing gear
during flight, is still missing, according to Pence.
   A Flying Tigers supervisor said the loss of the door caused no
problems for the plane.
