<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-89 1344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BosketTrial     02-19 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bosket Trial,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>Self-Described `Monster' On Trial For Attempted Murder Of Prison
Guard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN ROACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A self-described ``monster,'' a thrill
killer at 15 whose reputation is that of New York's most dangerous
inmate, is defending himself at his attempted murder trial and
trying to put the system on trial.
   Willie Bosket Jr., charged with stabbing a prison guard, is
shackled hand and foot in court but when he sits down at the defense
table, he flashes a smile at reporters and surveys the scene before
turning his attention to the neatly prepared files on his desk.
   He's not proclaiming innocence _ he admitted in opening arguments
that he stabbed the guard.
   Articulate and intelligent at the trial, Bosket said he hopes his
appearance will focus attention on problems he perceives within the
state's legal system. He says he stabbed the guard to retaliate
against injustices committed against him in prison, but the
prosecutor calls him a master manipulator.
   ``Each and every day I stand in this courtroom, I laugh at this
system because there ain't a damn thing that it can do to me except
to deal with the monster that it has created,'' Bosket said in his
opening statement.
   Courtrooms are nothing new for Bosket, 26, who has been shuffled
in and out of the legal system since he was 9 years old.
   ``I'm a monster that's come back to haunt this system and I will
dog this system until it is in its grave,'' Bosket promised in 1987.
   At the time the guard was stabbed at the Shawangunk Correctional
Facility on April 16, 1988, Bosket was serving 25 years to life for
assault, arson and being a persistent felon. He also had three years
remaining to serve on a previous conviction.
   In 1978, at age 15, Bosket prompted legislators to change the way
the state treats violent juveniles when he murdered two men and
injured another in an eight-day crime spree.
   He told authorities he did it ``for the experience.'' New York
City Mayor Edward Koch called him a ``willful, mad-dog killer.''
   Bosket was tried as a juvenile and sentenced to only five years.
But later that year, bowing to public pressure, then-Gov. Hugh Carey
and the Legislature enacted tougher juvenile laws that allow
teen-agers under 16 to be tried as adults for violent crimes.
   Bosket grew up in Harlem, the product of a broken home. He never
knew his father, Willie Bosket Sr., who graduated Phi Beta Kappa
from the University of Kansas while a federal prison inmate and
eventually died in an escape attempt.
   He once boasted to a detective that he had a record of robbery
arrests that began when he was 9. By age 10, he had been convicted
of attacking a younger child with a knife and sent to a detention
center. At age 12, Bosket was diagnosed by a psychiatrist as an
``emotional zombie.''
   After the guard was stabbed, a special ``box'' cell was built for
Bosket at the Woodbourne Correctional Facility in Sullivan County.
His meals are slipped in through a slot cut into iron bars.
Television cameras monitor his every move, 24 hours a day.
   When Bosket leaves his cell for any reason, he must first stick
his feet through a slot to be manacled and then his hands to be
cuffed. Three guards watch him when he gets his daily hour of
exercise, alone in a small, fenced-in area. The prisoner's hands and
feet remain manacled.
   Ulster County Judge Francis J. Vogt ruled that Bosket also must
remain in shackles during this trial, his hands and legs manacled
and linked to a chain around his waist.
   In spite of those restraints, Bosket has conducted his
cross-examinations with intelligent, articulate questions. Referring
to himself in the third-person, he has strayed from a professional
demeanor only occasionally, smiling or chuckling to himself when
something did not go his way.
   ``He clearly has established intelligence and also knowledge of
the courtroom,'' Chief Assistant District Attorney Donald Williams
said during a break in the trial Thursday.
   ``I'm not surprised. He's one of the most manipulative people
I've ever come across,'' Williams added. ``Appearances can be
deceiving.''
   When it's all over, Bosket knows he will return to his cell,
where even the guards are forbidden to talk to him.
   If convicted, Bosket could be sentenced to another prison term of
up to 25 years to life, which would have to be served consecutively
to his present sentence.
</TEXT>
