<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Nuclear     02-19 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Nuclear,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Plans First Permanent Nuclear Waste Dumps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China is making plans to build its first permanent
nuclear waste dumps in preparation for its first nuclear power
stations, an official report said Sunday.
   The first two dumps likely will be in Zhejiang province on the
east coast, where a 300-megawatt nuclear power plant is to start
operating next year, and in northwest China where nuclear weapons
are tested, China Daily said.
   The newspaper quoted Pan Ziqiang, director of the safety
department of state-run National Nuclear Industry Corp., as saying
that all China's nuclear waste has been put in concrete basement
storage facilities good for only 10 years.
   He said the plan is to move the waste to proposed new facilities
of steel containers buried 15 to 90 feet underground.
   Most of China's nuclear waste has been generated by the military,
but growing amounts are being produced by scientific labs, hospitals
and non-military industries.
   The start-up of the Qinshan nuclear power plant in Zhejiang next
year and of the 1,800-megawatt Daya Bay plant in southeast China's
Guangdong province by 1993 will add substantially to the amount of
waste produced.
   The China Daily did not say how much nuclear waste currently is
in temporary storage, the amount the new power plants will produce,
nor the planned capacity of the proposed new dumps.
   In recent years China has decided to turn to nuclear power to
compensate for dwindling supplies of coal and other fossil fuels,
which hamper economic development.
</TEXT>
