<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-89 1441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     02-19 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILLINGS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Man, it's cold in North Dakota. So cold,
says Byron Chamberlain, that the state should rename itself _ to
Manitscolda.
   Chamberlain, a high school assistant football coach from
Sheridan, Wyo., was declared the winner Sunday in the Billings
(Mont.) Gazette's tongue-in-cheek contest to rename North Dakota.
   The Gazette's contest was in response to a campaign by North
Dakota state Sen. Tim Mathern to rename the state ``Dakota.''
Mathern said he wanted to dispel the notion that his state is some
sort of arctic wasteland, and blamed the ``north'' in North Dakota
for the misconception.
   But Gazette readers didn't buy that line, as most of the 159
entries in the Gazette's contest zeroed in on the state's propensity
for cold winters.
   There was ``Darn Dacolda,'' ``Zipdacoatup,'' ``Weardakotanhat,''
``Saskatchacolda,'' ``Subtopia'' and, for those who put things
bluntly, ``Land of the Frozen Dead.''
   Chamberlain's first-place prize was a one-way bus ticket from
Billings to Bismarck, N.D., or the cash equivalent of $45. He said
he'd take the money.
   By the way, the warmest it got Saturday in Bismarck was 5 degrees.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GARY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While other English researchers pore over the
works of Shakespeare, Faulkner and Hemingway, Ruth K. MacDonald
prefers to analyze ``The Cat in the Hat,'' ``Green Eggs and Ham,''
and ``Horton Hears a Who!''
   MacDonald, head of the English and philosophy department at
Purdue University-Calumet, may be the country's top expert on
Theodor Seuss Geisel _ known to children around the world as Dr.
Seuss.
   ``We know as much as we can know about Shakespeare, but we don't
know much about Seuss. What we do know is scanty,'' says MacDonald,
the author of ``Dr. Seuss,'' a critical analysis of the acclaimed
children's author.
   MacDonald credits the playfulness of Geisel's language for his
enduring popularity, and notes that his books' themes let children
be children.
   ``He has loud and rowdy stories. You don't get rewarded for being
good but for being outrageous,'' she says. ``There is a sense he
appealed to the baby boomers becasue he played with language, pushed
to the edge and encouraged free thinking and experimentation.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sculpting figures from balloons, clown
props and clowning philosophies became serious business for about
250 students at the 1989 Clown School.
   Students and instructors spent part of Saturday visiting three
hospital and five nursing homes in Jefferson City to put their
knowledge to use. As Christian clowns, the students try to spread
cheer to sick adults and children in hospitals, nursing home
residents, churchgoers and others.
   ``It helps the new clowns learn how people are going to respond
to them in clown makeup,'' said Kay Hardage, coordinator of the
school sponsored by the Missouri Baptist Convention. ``But it also
gives us a chance to touch the people in nursing homes and
hospitals.''
   John and Susan Burns of Auxvasse were attending their fourth
Clown School.
   ``You lose your inhibitions when you put a face on and a funny
suit,'' Burns said. ``You figure, `Well, you look strange and funny
anyway, you may as well act that way.' It's a lot easier to approach
people, and people will approach you.''
</TEXT>
