<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-89 1444EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StrandedDancers     02-19 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stranded Dancers,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Dancers Leave After Being Stranded Two Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dance troupe from the Soviet Union is back on
tour again with a new schedule of appearances after being stranded
for two weeks when their financial backing fell apart.
   The 59 members of the Donetsk State Opera and Ballet Theatre set
out by bus Saturday for a Sunday night performance in North Branch,
N.J., ending an unexpected two-week stay at the Belvedere Hotel.
   Hotel front desk manager Donald Steurnagle, 31, had tears in his
eyes when he embraced each of the departing Ukrainian performers.
   ``I've been in the hotel business 10 years, and I've never been
involved personally with guests before,'' Steurnagle said after they
left. ``They were such good people. They brought me gifts all the
time. I will miss them.''
   The ballet troupe had planned a 15-city U.S. tour.
   But when the Soviets refused to allow three well-known dancers to
join the company for its American debut performances, U.S. and
Mexican investors withheld $200,000 in financial support, saying the
three stars had been promised.
   That left the troupe of young, relatively unknown dancers in the
lurch and cast into doubt the future of their performances in such
cities as Columbus, Ohio, and Chicago.
   While U.S. benefactors scrambled to find backing for a new tour,
contributors donated food, liquor and money. The Belvedere and the
Lyric Opera contributed meals. The Lyric held a benefit performance.
Trips were arranged to the National Aquarium and the U.S. Figure
Skating Championships in Baltimore. The United States Information
Agency helped arrange a White House trip.
   Finally, last weekend, a New York concert management firm, ICM
Artists, and the Howard Gilman Foundation in New York announced the
booking at North Branch, plus seven performances at New York's City
Center, to be followed by seven more performances in Washington.
Other cities have been added as well.
   Mikhail Baryshnikov, artistic director of the American Ballet
Theater and a director of the Gilman foundation, and who lived in
Gilman's home after defecting from the Soviet Union in the 1970s,
offered scenery, costumes and rehearsal space.
   Vladimir Shukmeikim, the troupe's artistic director, said
Saturday the dancers had dreaded returning to the Soviet Union under
a cloud of apparent artistic failure.
   ``I think this situation was so unusual, and it would have been
difficult to explain that it was not our fault but the impresarios
who signed the contract,'' he said.
   At Saturday's departure, Lyric president Robert Pomory shared
embraces and kisses with the dancers and several of them threw him
into the air in celebration of his support.
   ``I'm their brother and Mr. Pomory is their father,'' Steurnagle
said.
   ``It's like I developed a whole new entire family,'' Pomory added.
</TEXT>
