<FIRST>u i AM-Afghan-Rebels Bjt   02-19 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan-Rebels, Bjt,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrilla Leaders Paralyzed By Differences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moderate Afghan guerrillas unhappy
with nominees for an interim government for their nation on Sunday
walked out of a meeting called to elect a president and prime
minister.
   Qaribur Rehman Saeed, a spokesman for a guerrilla-operated news
agency, said the special Consultative Council of about 400 delegates
will meet again Monday despite the standoff involving the seven
Afghan guerrilla groups based in Pakistan.
   Four of the seven guerrilla parties are made up of hard-line
Islamic fundamentalists who want to establish a strict
fundamentalist state in Afghanistan. The three moderate groups want
a more liberal state similar to the governments prior to the
communist coup in 1978.
   Moderate factions walked out Sunday, and sources said even
representatives of hard-line guerrilla groups argued against a
proposed government headed by Ahmad Shah as prime minister.
   ``Ahmad Shah is a product of disunity, not unity,'' a guerrilla
official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Shah is a senior political official of the hard-line
Ittehad-e-Islami guerrilla group.
   ``We won't be part of this shameful government,'' said a
spokesman for the moderate National Islamic Front of Afghanistan. He
also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Sources who attended the council session said members of that
group were among the guerrillas who walked out.
   The nominee for acting president of the interim government is
Mohammad Nabi Mohammadi, head of the moderate
Harakat-i-Inquilab-i-Islami guerrilla group.
   The guerrilla groups are deeply divided over sharing power, and
the nominations of Mohammadi and Shah were seen as a compromise on
who would lead Afghanistan if its Soviet-back government collapses.
   The Soviets withdrew their last troops from Afghanistan on
Wednesday and the guerrillas have vowed to overthrow the communist
government of President Najib.
   On Saturday, Saeed said a vote scheduled for Sunday on the
nominations was expected to be a formality because the council
delegates were in agreement.
   After Sunday's session, however, he said it was not clear when
the vote would be held. The council also is to appoint a Cabinet.
   The council, which convened Feb. 10, was expected to conclude
after the vote.
   If the guerrillas seize power, they would hold elections within
six months to form an elected council, or shura, that would appoint
a permanent head of state and ratify a government, officials say.
   Outside the meeting site, a Pakistani police officer shot to
death a fellow officer. Police officials said the shooting was
unrelated to the Afghan council session. Some witnesses said it was
a vengeance killing.
   As the guerrilla leaders began leaving the compound where the
council meeting was held, some stopped momentarily to watch as an
ambulance removed the body of the slain police officer.
   Afghans and journalists milling outside the meeting fled for
cover when the other officer opened fire.
   He paced nervously in front of the body for more than 30 minutes
and kept plainclothes officers at bay.
   A superior then arrived and talked him into surrendering. He was
disarmed and fell to his knees and wept.
</TEXT>
