<FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PoliceShortage     02-19 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Police Shortage,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crime Growing Faster than Police Force in Nation's Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Retransmitting to fix category code</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of police has not kept pace with the
crime rate in the District of Columbia, the murder capital of the
United States, and union officials are urging the mayor to hire more
officers.
   ``The homicide rate so far this year is terrible proof that we
cannot wait,'' Gary Hankins, chairman of the Fraternal Order of
Police labor committee, recently told Mayor Marion S. Barry Jr.
   The number of crimes reported in the city grew from 52,431 in
1986 to 61,884 last year, but the number of police remained the
same, 3,958 officers.
   The crime rate is growing even faster this year, with 75 people
murdered by last week, putting the city on a course for 600 murders,
shattering the record 372 set last year.
   The crisis prompted Police Chief Maurice T. Turner Jr. to declare
a crime emergency starting Tuesday. The chief city attorney,
Frederick D. Cooke Jr., said the step would allow police to reassign
officers without giving the 28 days notice required in an agreement
with the Fraternal Order of Police.
   Police blame ``crack'' cocaine for the upsurge in crime, and say
drugs are responsible for 60 percent of the murders this year and
last.
   Morale on the force is at an all-time low because so many young
people are being drawn into the lucrative drug trade, say union
officials.
   ``This can't go on forever,'' Hankins warned. ``There's no
slowdown in the drug trade, and burnout is getting to be a real
problem.''
   The number of police officers has dipped since the early 1970's,
when there were 5,000. The number was 3,958 from 1984 through last
year, rose to 4,130, this year, and was slated to increase by 200 by
1990.
   Police chief Turner says that the key is not adding police but
intercepting drugs before they hit the street.
   ``You can always use more officers, but I think more officers
will end up in more drug arrests,'' Turner said. ``We have to attack
the supply side because if we don't do that, we'll get to the point
where 20,000 officers won't be enough.''
   City jails and courts are already clogged by drug arrests.
   Since the start of Operation Clean Sweep against drugs in August
1986, more than 45,000 people have been arrested for drug-related
offenses. City prisons are so overcrowded that inmates are being
sent to facilities as distant as Walla Walla, Wash.
   The city may have neither the money nor the means to increase the
force rapidly. The 1988 budget was $34 million in deficit. And the
number of officers eligible to retire is high, 250 annually over the
next three years.
   ``It will take years to actually bring these (recruits) on board
and for them to mature to a high level of effectiveness,'' Hankins
said. ``In the meantime, we'll be losing officers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890219-0060 </DOCNO>
