<FIRST>u i AM-Honduras-Attack     02-19 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Attack,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldier Injured In Bus Attack To Be Transferred To Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. soldier wounded when a bomb
was thrown at a bus carrying American servicemen will be moved to a
military hospital in Panama and then sent home, officials said
Sunday.
   U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Anne M. Sigmund told The Associated
Press by telephone that 22-year-old Russell E. Miller of Hackett,
Ark., will be taken Monday to Gorgas Military Hospital in Panama.
   Sigmund said, ``His injuries are not serious and he is out of
danger. In Panama will be hospitalized for a few days and return to
the United States.''
   She did not describe Miller's injuries. He was being treated
Sunday in a hospital at Enrique Soto Cano Air Base outside
Comayagua, 60 miles northwest of the capital.
   Miller was among three soldiers injured when a bus carrying 28
U.S. servicemen was bombed in Comayagua.
   The embassy spokeswoman said Miller and the two other servicemen
injured in Saturday's explosion belong to the 183rd engineer's
National Guard batallion from Fort Smith, Ark. She said the other
soldiers, who arrived Feb. 4 for a two-week training mission, are
returning to the United States.
   The other two soldiers were treated and released with minor
injuries, officials said Saturday. The spokeswoman would not
identify them.
   Two Hondurans walking nearby were slightly injured by the blast
in Comayagua.
   Officials said no one has claimed responsibility for the attack.
   The explosive was a crude device rigged with dynamite, said Maj.
Juan Blas Salazar, regional police chief.
   ``We want to find those reponsible for this attack. For this we
can count on the help of the U.S. military,'' he added.
   Police said the bus was attacked at 12:10 p.m. Saturday as the
soldiers were en route to the Enrique Soto Cano Air Base, the
principal center of operations for U.S. manuevers in Honduras.
   More than 1,800 U.S. soldiers arrived in Honduras last month for
joint maneuvers with the Honduran military. Most of the soldiers
come in groups of 400-500 and stay for two weeks.
   Police said the blast damaged the bus, a parked car, a school and
a hotel.
   This was the third terrorist attack against U.S. soldiers, who
have been conducting maneuvers in Honduras since 1982.
   On Aug. 7, 1987, a bomb injured six American soldiers and six
Honduran civilians in a Comayagua restaurant.
   On Feb. 1, seven vehicles carrying more than 30 American soldiers
were attacked by unidentified gunmen in northern Yoro province. No
one was injured.
   Violence has increased lately in Honduras. Manuel Rugama, a
leader of the Nicaraguan rebels, was killed Jan. 7.
   On Jan. 23, Carlos Dias, the attorney for suspected Honduran drug
trafficker Juan Ramon Matta, was fatally shot.
   On Jan. 25, Gen. Gustavo Alvarez Martinez, former head of the
Honduran armed forces, was slain by gunmen.
   Leftist groups have protested the U.S. maneuvers in Honduras and
the presence of 11,000 Contras along the Nicaraguan border. Leftists
are suspected in the Rugama and Alvarez Martinez killings.
</TEXT>
