<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Farmers     02-19 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Farmers,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmer Activists Hold Joyful Gathering</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Miners, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RZESZOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 people at a Sunday Mass
in southeast Poland recalled the birth eight years ago of the banned
independent farmers' union and expressed optimism it soon will
operate freely again.
   Government and opposition negotiators agreed in principle last
week to legalize Rural Solidarity. The union representing the Polish
countryside was banned along with workers' Solidarity in the
December 1981 martial law crackdown.
   Solidarity and Rural Solidarity are separate but mutually
supporting organizations.
   ``Today we are witnessing the beginning of a process in which the
truth is becoming visible again,'' Bishop Ignacy Tokarczuk said in a
sermon at the service marking the anniversary of the Feb. 18, 1981
agreement that legalized Rural Solidarity.
   ``We welcome with cautious hope the understanding that it is
better to talk than to fight,'' he said.
   The bishop said they were witnessing the ``bankruptcy'' of a
political system without God.
   He warned against being too trusting of authorities' promises.
   ``We have to talk but do not allow cheating,'' he said. ``We have
the support of a united society which is pressing and demanding its
rights.''
   At the end of the Mass, messages of support from workers around
the country were read.
   The huge modern church on the outskirts of Rzeszow, 190 miles
southeast of Warsaw, was filled literally to the rafters, with
worshipers crammed into the staircase leading to its roof.
   ``The moods are so radical that people demand that we prepare
some kind of protest for them,'' said Artur Balazs, a member of
Rural Solidarity's national council and one of the negotiators at
the current talks with the government on Poland's future.
   Balazs and union chairman Jozef Slisz said they were preparing a
draft of a new law about legalizing Rural Solidarity.
   ``We have been talking to farmers for two days here and now we
are drawing our conclusions,'' said Slisz. ``It has been a good
lesson for us. We will go to Warsaw and see what the effects are.''
   The farmers' movement continued to function despite the ban and
leaders said there has been a surge of interest in recent weeks.
``More and more farmers are joining the union and there is a great
revival of the movement in the countryside,'' said Slisz.
   He said farmers' councils already are functioning openly in 36 of
Poland's 49 provinces and he expects the number to grow.
   Slisz said farmers worried most about the low prices they receive
for their produce, which he said has not kept pace with increases in
the cost of seed, fertilizer, fodder and machinery.
</TEXT>
