<FIRST>r a AM-BundyParents     02-19 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bundy Parents,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cards And Letters Express Sympathy For Bundy Parents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bundy Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of sympathetic cards and letters
are helping Louise and John Bundy emerge from the dark shadow of
their serial-killer son, but they remain upset over the celebration
accompanying his execution.
   ``I can go along with people believing in the death penalty, but
you can't be happy about it. It isn't to be a joyous celebration,''
Mrs. Bundy said in the couple's first interview since Ted Bundy's
execution Jan. 24.
   In a story on the interview Sunday, The Morning News Tribune of
Tacoma reported the couple also has received some 400 cards from
people who were moved by the suffering of the killer's mother and
stepfather.
   ``This is just to let you know, all people are not cruel and
sadistic people. My thoughts and prayers are with you all,'' one
woman wrote.
   Ted Bundy died in Florida's electric chair for the 1978 murder of
12-year-old Kimberly Diane Leach of Lake City, Fla. Some
investigators believe he may have killed up to 100 people.
   Until her son started confessing to at least 23 murders in the
days before his execution, Mrs. Bundy said she believed he was
innocent.
   ``When his confessions came out, it was all like a blow right
between the eyes,'' she said. ``This was not the Ted we had raised _
we never saw anything to indicate it.''
   Bundy was born in 1946, at a home for unwed mothers, and the boy
was raised partly by his grandparents _ Mrs. Bundy's parents _
during his first few years. Mrs. Bundy married John Bundy in 1951,
and he then adopted young Ted.
   But Mrs. Bundy said her son had a normal childhood, and
discounted her son's contention during his final days that exposure
to pornography kept by his grandfather had affected him.
   ``We did everything parents of the '50s and '60s did,'' she said,
even down to reading Dr. Spock.
   Bundy wrote his parents a final letter on the eve of his death,
saying, in part, ``Nothing I can say can ease your pain. It is a
terrible thing, I know, but I have to try to make it right _ to tell
the truth.''
   ``I do love you. You were wonderful parents.''
   The night before the execution, the Bundys remained at home until
midnight, talking with Ted on the telephone and with visitors. The
family went to a friend's house at midnight, and waited out the
morning with about 30 friends and church members.
   ``Nobody had to call and tell us it was over. We knew it,'' she
said. ``Along about 7:15 or so _ I guess it was 4:15 here _ I just
knew that Ted was all right. I knew it was over. I felt more at
peace at that moment than I had for 13 years.''
   On the day he was executed, crowds of people gathered outside the
Florida penitentiary where they waved frying pans and shouted
``Burn, Bundy, Burn!''
   Mrs. Bundy said she was angered by the comments of an
investigator that her son was born to kill.
   ``No beautiful child is born to kill. He was not born to do
that,'' she said.
   Her husband, John, said he and his wife have been unable to
determine why Ted became a killer.
   ``We talk about it and try to figure out down the line what it
was. Like I say, it was something he more or less kept under
cover,'' he said.
   ``So far as figuring out why _ it's not going to be figured
out,'' said Bundy.
</TEXT>
