<FIRST>r a AM-ChurchProtest     02-19 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Protest,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissidents Rally Outside Bridgeport Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 people gathered outside St.
Michael the Archangel Roman Catholic Church on Sunday morning,
kneeling, singing and praying before the locked doors of the
building that protesters had occupied for nearly a week.
   Diocese leaders closed the predominantly Polich church until
further notice early Saturday after police removed dissident
parishioners who had occupied the church to protest the transfers of
a popular pastor and an assistant priest and to demand that the
current pastor leave.
   ``The doors are locked, but we want to show the world we won't
quit,'' said Halina Chmiel of Milford, one of the leaders of the
protest.
   The Sunday morning rally lasted about an hour without any
incident.
   Mrs. Chmiel's husband, Henry, 35, and Franciszek Wojenski, 53, of
Bridgeport, were the only ones arrested when 40 police officers, who
arrived on a school bus, marched single file to clear the church
early Saturday morning.
   The others left voluntarily, ending the protesters' ``pray-in''
that began Feb. 11. Regular church activities continued during the
protest.
   The police action came hours after negotiations between church
authorities and the protesters ended in an emotional, shouting melee
inside the church. The group rejected appeals to leave from the Rev.
Laurence R. Bronkiewicz, the diocese's vicar for clergy, and a
visiting Franciscan superior from Gdansk, Poland, the Very Rev. Leon
Rawalski.
   The protesters also rejected an appeal from the former assistant
pastor they want to return, the Rev. Roman Palaszewski, who is being
transferred back to Poland. He made a surprise visit to the church
late Friday, his first appearance since his removal in December.
   No officials of the diocese were available for comment Sunday
about when the church would be reopened, the diocese answering
service said.
   The protesters charge that the current church leadership are
diluting the Polish traditions of the church, which is located in a
predominantly Hispanic neighborhood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
