<FIRST>r a AM-RareFerns     02-19 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rare Ferns,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extremely Rare Ferns Discovered in Aleutians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The known world population of one of the
rarest plants in North America has increased more than tenfold with
the discovery of about 100 of the endangered plants in the Aleutian
Islands
   Before the discovery of the Aleutian-Shield fern plants last
summer on Adak Island, biologists thought only six of the plants
were left on Earth. Botanists examining plant life on the island's
Mount Reed found the new pocket of Shield ferns not far from
previously known plants.
   The fern is unique to two islands in the Aleutians. Botanists say
they believe it is a survivor from pre-glacial times, living in a
few mountain areas that escaped the glaciers. The harsh climate in
those areas and possible grazing by animals prevented the ferns from
spreading after the glaciers receded, they say.
   The discovery has raised hopes the ferns will not become extinct.
   Biologists from the federal Fish and Wildlife Service are
studying ways to protect the surviving plants and help the
population grow, perhaps by growing the plants in a controlled
environment, said Walter O. Stieglitz, regional director for the
agency.
</TEXT>
