<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     02-19 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Group Initiates Fresh Bout Of Political Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new group calling itself the ``Black
Cats'' executed 20 Sinhalese men in central villages in the first
major violence since election results were announced last week,
military officials said Sunday.
   The officials said the victims were members of the People's
Liberation Front, an ultranationalist Sinhalese militant group
opposing the Sinhalese-dominated government's moves to grant limited
autonomy to Tamils in the north and east.
   In the north, at least four Tamils were killed and six injured in
factional clashes between two groups of rebel Tamil militias,
military officials said.
   Soldiers discovered the bodies of the 20 young Sinhalese men late
Saturday, shot through the head with their arms tied behind their
backs, many of them partially burned, said officials of the military
joint operations command, who cannot be quoted under briefing rules.
   The bodies were found in the villages of Vijithapura and Siripura
in Anuradhapura district, 105 miles northeast of Colombo in the
Sinhalese heartland of central Sri Lanka, officials said.
   Notices found near the bodies claimed the killings were carried
out by the ``Black Cats,'' the officials said.
   Officials said they had never heard of the group.
   The killings were the first since President Ranasinghe
Premadasa's United National Party won parliamentary polls in results
declared Thursday, the officials said.
   At least 1,000 people, including 14 candidates for the
legislature, were killed during the five-week election campaign that
began Jan. 6, threatened by Sinhalese and Tamil militants.
   Most of the deaths were blamed on the People's Liberation Front,
while police blamed Tamil extremists for a few killings, mostly in
the north of the island.
   Militant Tamils claim they are discriminated against by the
mostly Buddhist Sinhalese majority who make up 75 per cent of the
island's population, in education, employment and culture.
   They have waged a secessionist war for an independent Tamil
homeland since 1983, in which more than 8,500 people, mostly
Sinhalese civilians, have been killed.
   Also Saturday, four members of a former Tamil guerrilla
organization, the Eelam Revolutionary Organization of Students were
killed in fights between them and members of the Eelam People's
Revolutionary Liberation Front. Six others were injured, military
officials said.
   The clashes took place in Jaffna in the north and Batticaloa in
eastern Sri Lanka, but details were not immediately available, the
officials said.
   Mostly Hindu Tamils comprise 18 per cent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people and are in a slight majority in northern and eastern
Sri Lanka.
   Sinhalese militants also have unleashed a bloody campaign against
the government for making too many concessions to minority Tamils.
More than 1,500 people, mostly Sinhalese government supporters, have
fallen victim to the Sinhalese militant backlash since July 1987.
</TEXT>
