<FIRST>r a AM-SkunkBoom     02-19 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skunk Boom,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posh Marin County Raises Stink About Booming Skunk Population</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN RAFAEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several communities in well-to-do Marin
County are raising a stink about a booming skunk population and some
residents are getting desperate.
   ``People are calling in saying they are seeing them (skunks) all
over the place, not just in the rural areas,'' said Wendy O'Neil, an
assistant at the Marin Wildlife Center. ``It's really widespread.
   ``We're getting some pretty unusual requests, too. Like people
asking where to buy stun guns.''
   The wildlife center has been averaging 20 to 30 calls a day about
the stinky critters and the Marin Humane Society is taking about 25
complaints a day from people saying the little black and whites have
set up housekeeping in their basements.
   The society is planning a seminar called ``Skunks: Whose House Is
It, Anyway?''
   Esther Silver, owner of a Point Reyes Station bookstore, knows
only too well.
   During the past three weeks, Silver has trapped six skunks under
her shop and adjacent rental unit, and is trying to catch more.
Meanwhile, she's burning scented candles in her shop.
   ``It's a constant struggle,'' she said. ``You can't even drive
over the hill to San Rafael without going through three areas of
skunk smells. Everybody's complaining.''
</TEXT>
