<FIRST>r a AM-Spaceport-Environment     02-19 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spaceport-Environment,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Opposed To One Proposed Spaceport Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists across the country will
fight attempts to build the nation's first commercial spaceport at a
site on the northern part of Kennedy Space Center, a Florida
activist warns.
   ``This is one of those fall-on-your-sword-and-die issues,'' said
Charles Lee, senior vice president of the Florida Audubon Society.
   The state hopes to build a $58 million Spaceport Florida within
three years at either Kennedy Space Center or the adjacent Cape
Canaveral Air Force Station.
   But more than a dozen environmentalist and civic groups plan to
oppose any attempt to locate the spaceport on a part of the space
center known as Shiloh that is managed as a park by the Merritt
Island National Wildlife Refuge.
   ``If the Shiloh site remains, you will probably see opposition to
Spaceport Florida on a nationwide level,'' Lee said.
   Building at Shiloh would increase construction costs by 20
percent, but state officials prefer it because they want to avoid
restrictions on funding and access posed by using a military
installation, according to Chris Shove, director of the state
Department of Commerce's space programs office.
   Lee said letting public officials give chunks of parkland for
commercial ventures would set a bad precedent. The launch facility
also would restrict public access to the wildlife refuge and
Canaveral National Seashore, and highly toxic rocket fuels would
endanger nearby environmentally sensitive areas, critics of the
proposal say.
   ``We all support putting it at Canaveral Air Force Station,''
said Reid Hughes, a Volusia County environmentalist. ``Perhaps it
would be best to eliminate the controversy now and drop the Shiloh
site.''
   State officials met with environmental and civic groups Friday in
Orlando to answer questions, and more meetings will be held.
   ``If significant environmental impact is shown at Shiloh, the
project will be stopped,'' Shove said. ``But I don't think there's
been any evidence of that yet.''
   Under the Shiloh plan, the state initially would build one launch
pad on a 50-acre area. As demand increased for commercial launches,
three more pads could be added, he said.
   At the Canaveral base, three launch pads abandoned by the
military could be used after extensive renovations.
   State officials expect to pick the final site within six months
and start a detailed environmental study of both areas shortly
after, Shove said. But if the Legislature refuses Gov. Bob
Martinez's request for the first $10 million for the project this
spring, Spaceport Florida may be shelved.
</TEXT>
