<HEAD>Eleven Wounded as Palestinians Launch Three-Day Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with more wounded, details; picks
up 11th pvs, `We see...,' minor editing to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops wounded 11 Arabs during sporadic clashes
on Sunday, Arab reports said, and Palestinians in the occupied lands
shut down businesses to begin a three-day strike to press for an
independent homeland.
   In Jerusalem, shrieks, scuffles and a cry of ``Death to all
terrorists!'' disrupted the funeral of Shlomo Cohen, a 21-year-old
soldier who was stabbed to death Saturday as he walked unarmed near
Jerusalem's walled Old City.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin blamed the Palestine Liberation
Organization for Cohen's death and the suspected kidnapping of
another Israeli soldier, Sgt. Avi Sasportaz, who has been missing
for three days.
   ``The two incidents, it is not possible that they were not
organized by a group and I believe that it was connected to a terror
group,'' Rabin said on Israel radio. ``Read that as the PLO.''
   ``I recommend to those overseas, who cling to the foot of (PLO
chairman Yasser) Arafat, the PLO is terror,'' he said. ``The PLO has
not rejected terror, both in Israel and outside.''
   Thousands of soldiers, police and civilian volunteers continued
the search for Sasportaz on Sunday, and his mother Rachel issued an
impassioned plea on Israel radio, begging the kidnappers to ``Please
give me him alive, don't kill him.''
   The three-day general strike to demand an independent Palestine
is the longest work stoppage called by pro-PLO underground leaders
since Palestinians began their 14-month-old revolt against Israel's
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Arab news reports said the first strike day was fully observed.
But Israel radio said some Palestinian workers showed up for jobs in
Israel.
   Soldiers trying to prevent stoning attacks Sunday clamped curfews
on three neighborhoods and refugee camps in the Gaza Strip,
confining 45,000 Palestinians to their homes, and sealed off 13
alleys in the Khan Yunis refugee camp.
   Sporadic protests erupted, however, and troops were stoned and
responded with gunfire in at least three incidents, wounding eleven
people, according to Arab reports.
   The army confirmed five of the wounded and said it was
investigating the other incidents.
   In Jerusalem, 1,000 mourners held an emotional military funeral
for Cohen, who was on leave and in civilian clothes when he was
attacked.
   ``We see that the people of the PLO and their supporters speak
with knives,'' Prime Minister Yitzak Shamir told mourners.
   No Palestinian group has claimed responsibility for the killing.
   ``Jewish blood cannot be spilled without being avenged!'' shouted
one man, among a few people who disrupted the service for about 10
minutes. Other mourners tried to calm down protesters, who finally
were removed by police.
   Cohen, a former seminary student, was the 16th Israeli killed
since the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987. At least 383 Palestinians
have been killed in that time.
   In another development:
   _Israel radio said an 18-year-old Palestinian jailed for security
offenses was found stabbed to death in Beersheba prison in southern
Israel. Police believe he was killed by another Arab inmate for as
yet unknown reasons, the radio said.
   _Israel ordered prominent Arab journalist Samaan Khouri detained
for six months without trial after he participated in recent
meetings with left-wing Israelis. Khouri works part-time for Agence
France Presse news agency and was detained for 4{ months as a
suspected PLO activist last year.
