<FIRST>r a AM-PrincipalResigns     02-19 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Principal Resigns,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Principal Admits Some Allegations of Racial Remarks, Administrator
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former principal accused of making
racist remarks about blacks to white students acknowledges some of
the allegations made by black teachers, a school administrator said.
   Charles Walker, who is white, resigned Friday as principal of
Northeast High School because of a letter from several black
teachers alleging that he told white cheerleaders that associating
with blacks would degrade them, and that ``black students are
inferior to them because of their color.''
   ``Mr. Walker confirmed some of it but not all of it. In Mr.
Walker's opinion, there was sufficient substance to render him
ineffective,'' Donald Hoover, associate superintendent of East Baton
Rouge Parish schools, said Saturday.
   Hoover said Walker acknowledged an error in judgment in calling
the meeting with the white students, but that the situation ``was
not as dramatic as painted.''
   ``Some of the things that letter said he had said are not true,''
Hoover added. ``Stating outright that blacks are inferior to whites,
Mr. Walker vehemently denies that.''
   Walker has an unlisted phone number and could not be reached for
comment. He will be assigned to the school system's central office,
Hoover said.
   ``I think it was a good move to move him out of the reach of
children. People like that should not go into education in a
multiracial system,'' said G. Washington Eames, president of the
NAACP's chapter in Baton Rouge.
</TEXT>
