<HEAD>Fence Along Cliff Walk Spurs Outcry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A real-estate developer who recently
purchased one of Newport's famed mansions has riled some of his
neighbors by building a fence along the popular Cliff Walk.
   Joseph Mele, who paid $2 million for the mansion once owned by
novelist Edith Wharton, said he decided to build the fence because
hikers on the Cliff Walk were crossing his property and leaving
litter behind.
   A number of residents have complained in recent weeks that the
fence would force strollers onto dangerous rocks closer to the ocean
than the present route of the walk, which winds around several miles
of the Rhode Island coastline.
   ``The way he's pushing the walk out to the edge of the water,
he's putting people's lives in danger,'' said resident Robert Byron.
   ``I really dislike it when people say that I'm taking something
away, when I'm putting something up on my own property,'' said Mele,
of Washington, adding that he has left plenty of room for hikers.
   ``In some places, I've left them 30 yards,'' he said. ``Except
for a couple of places, I left enough room for people to walk side
by side.''
