<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Protest     02-19 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Protest,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorneys Say About 200 Fasting in Natal Province</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 black prisoners in Natal
province are refusing to eat until they receive the same sort of
attention that authorities gave another group of fasting inmates,
lawyers said Sunday.
   The Natal province prisoners have been on a hunger strike since
last week and their attorneys say they are trying to arrange a
meeting with Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok.
   Vlok last week met with another group of civil rights lawyers
representing about 200 other hunger strikers in the Cape and
Transvaal provinces. Vlok agreed to free a number of detainees in
the next two weeks.
   Both groups, whose members are being held without charges under
state of emergency regulations, began hunger strikes to demand that
they either be freed or charged.
   But lawyers for the Natal province hunger strikes, in a
statement, said they are unsure whether Vlok's promise applies to
their group.
   The attorneys said about 200 detainees are on a hunger strike in
the Westville prison in Durban, the prison at Pietermaritzburg, and
in police cells throughout the province.
   A total of about 300 prisoners initially went on a hunger strike
three weeks ago to protest their jailing. Some subsequently ended
their strike and others joined it. They are represented by two
groups of lawyers, and it was difficult to determine how many remain
on a hunger strike.
   More than 20 hunger strikers have been hospitalized, prompting
Vlok to hold meetings last week with lawyers, clergymen and
relatives of about 200 detainees.
   For the first time he received information other than that
supplied by his policemen on why certain people were considered a
danger to the community.
   Vlok said Saturday that in the future he would assign a senior
police officer to investigate factors such as family circumstances,
the detainee's attitudes and his job possibilities so that those
things can be considered in deciding whether a detainee should be
freed.
   Monitoring groups have said more than 30,000 people, mostly
black, have been detained for some period of time during the state
of emergency, which permits indefinite incarceration without charges
or trial.
   Vlok has never given a total figure, but the periodic reports he
must make to Parliament have added up to approximately 30,000. He
said two weeks ago that there were fewer than 1,000 people in
detention at that time.
   The national state of emergency was declared on June 12, 1986,
and some of the hunger strikers have been held without charge since
then.
</TEXT>
