<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Flooding 1stLd-Writethru a0724 02-19 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Flooding, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescue Under Way in Jungle Flood Zone</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with six grafs to UPDATE with 40 dead, details; picks
up 4th graf `The army...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue operations were stepped up Sunday in a
jungle-covered region in northern Peru where flooding has killed at
least 40 people, officials said.
   The National Civil Defense office in Lima said Prime Minister
Armando Villanueva toured the flooded zone Sunday and reported
afterwards that 40 people had been killed and 30 others were missing.
   Officials said a layer of mud deposited by the receeding waters
could conceal other victims.
   The rain-swollen Gera and Indoche rivers jumped their banks
Friday and flooded a dozen small villages and settlements near
Moyobamba, 450 miles northeast of Lima, city officials said.
   Hundreds of farm families near Shucyacu, a tiny village 20 miles
south of Moyobamba were temporarily been driven from their homes,
which were damaged or destroyed by the flood waters, Civil Defense
said.
   Several Lima newspapers on Sunday gave death toll figures of up
to 60, but Civil Defense authorities, speaking on condition of
anonymity, declined to confirm the newspaper numbers.
   The army base in Tarapoto, 55 miles south of the flooded zone,
said more than 30 people had been killed.
   The inundated region, cut by dozens of small rivers and streams
which swell during the current rainy season, is on the
jungle-covered slopes of the eastern Andes Mountains.
   The village of Shucyacu was hardest hit, Moyobamba officials
said. The leading edge of the flood waters, which carried mud, tree
trunks and other debris, swept away at least 50 of the hamlets small
wooden homes with thatched roofs.
   Officials said about 6,000 people, mainly from farm families,
live in the flooded region, but it is still unknown how many have
suffered damage or loss.
   El Comercio said 35 people were missing and the flooding
destroyed about 200 homes. The newspaper said the army had sent
earth-moving equipment to help clear away mud left by the flood
waters.
   Moyobamba city councilman Adrian Mendoza said the area's most
important crops of rice and corn were destroyed.
   Officials said rescue operations were stepped up Sunday after
being slowed a day earlier by stormy weather, bad roads and the
flood waters.
   The flooding was sparked by heavy runoff from recent torrential
rains in the high Andes Mountains and in the foothills surrounding
Moyobamba, authorities said.
</TEXT>
