<HEAD>Church Calls For Accord During Meeting Between Guerrillas, Parties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic Church on
Sunday urged guerrilla leaders and politicans to reach an accord
this week that will bring peace in the country.
   Guerrilla leaders and representatives of all major Salvadoran
political parties are to meet in Mexico on Monday to discuss a rebel
demand that the March 19 elections be delayed until September.
   The rebels say they will recognize the legitimacy of the next
elected government if the balloting were delayed, and if safeguards
against fraud were in place.
   Monsignor Gregorio Rosa Chavez, auxiliary archbishop of San
Salvador, said the date of elections ``is one of the points of the
(guerrilla) proposal most easily resolved.
   ``Our emphasis is this: how, by changing the date of elections,
do we achieve a complete guarantee that the war will end in by
September? If that can be achieved, I think that not only some
parties, but the immense majority would say `Of course, we'll change
the date of elections.'''
   The rebels have boycotted and condemned as sham the previous
elections this decade.
   The government of President Jose Napoleon Duarte and the armed
forces have all but ruled out acceptance of the guerrilla propsosal.
   Guillermo Ungo, presidential candidate of the leftist Democratic
Convergence and a participant in Monday's meeting, told The
Associated Press on Saturday he did not expect much to come of the
Mexico talks.
   A breakthrough would depend on unanimous acceptance of
postponement by the political parties. The rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance, which is favored to win in March, has opposed
postponement.
   An estimated 70,000 people have been killed in the 9-year-old
civil war between the leftist guerrillas and the U.S.-backed
government.
