<HEAD>Korchnoi Opposes Judge, Quits Tournament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINARES, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet-born chess player Viktor Korchnoi,
now a Swiss citizen, withdrew Sunday from the Seventh City of
Linares international chess tournament after organizers denied his
request to exclude a Soviet judge.
   Korchnoi told reporters he had sent a letter to the tournament's
organizers saying he would not play if Viktor Baturisnky of the
Soviet Union was the main judge.
   Korchnoi had problems with Baturinsky, a senior official in the
Soviet Chess Federation, when he played Anatoly Karpov in 1974, two
years before he sought asylum in the West. Karpov won 12.5-11.5.
   In his book ``Chess is My Life,'' Korchnoi accuses Baturisnky of
partiality in the match, in which he played Karpov for the right to
play Bobby Fischer of the United States for the world title.
   Korchnoi was scheduled to meet Vasili Ivanchuck of the Soviet
Union Sunday in the opening match of the 14-day tournament.
   ``I will only admit, as a great concession, that the organizers
could make (Baturinsky) a guest of honor, but nothing more,'' said
Korchnoi.
   Julio Gallardo, president of the Linares tournament organizing
committee, said Sunday he had not received Korchnoi's letter.
   Luis Rentero, technical director of the tournament, proposed that
Francisco Mena of Spain be the judge in the matches played by
Korchnoi, but he said Korchnoi refused.
   Korchnoi left for Madrid after a one-hour meeting between
players, judges and members of the organization, who confirmed
Baturinsky's position as main judge. He said he felt insulted by the
organizers.
   After Korchnoi left the tournament, the other players decided to
play as scheduled.
   Nigel Short of Britain defeated Karpov and Artur Yusupov of the
Soviet Union defeated fellow Soviet Andrei Sokolov.
   The three other matches in the opening round were adjourned. They
were: Jan Timman, Netherlands, v. Lajos Portisch, Hungary, Valeri
Gulkov, United States, v. Johan Hjartarson, Iceland, and Alexander
Beliavsky, Soviet Union, v. Ljomir Ljubojevic, Yugoslavia,
