<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Politics     02-19 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Politics,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secretary-Elect Calls for Unity, Pledges to Back Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only candidate to replace Premier Ciriaco De Mita
as leader of Italy's most powerful party said Sunday he would not
try to bring down the government.
   Arnaldo Forlani is expected to be named secretary of the
Christian Democrat Party during its five-day special congress, which
began Saturday.
   His nomination was seen as a major defeat for De Mita, who
considers Forlani too conservative to back his programs in
Parliament and a threat to De Mita's 10-month-old coalition
government.
   Forlani indicated Sunday that De Mita would have to heed the
wishes of a new leadership.
   In a 1{-hour speech to party delegates, Forlani called for
support for the government, which he said had lacked steady backing
as it tried to cut the huge public deficit.
   ``The government's existence will never be threatened by
maneuvers in the (party),'' Forlani said.
   ``But it is on (the issue of) an economic cure that the future of
the government and of the alliance (of governing parties) rides,''
he warned.
   The party secretary is seen by many as the most influential
politician in Italy, since the Christian Democrats have dominated
every government for four decades.
   De Mita's candidates for secretary were defeated in party
wrangling prior to the congress. Nonetheless, the premier tried to
ensure support for his programs by asking congress Saturday to give
his leadership a vote of confidence.
   In his speech at a sports stadium in a neighborhood built by
dictator Benito Mussolini, Forlani called for party unity and
indicated the government would receive continued support if it stuck
by the wishes of the party.
   ``If we (the Christian Democrats) proceed united, the government
also will be at an advantage and can reinforce its actions,''
Forlani said.
   De Mita, 61, from the party's left wing, insisted on remaining
party secretary when he became premier last April, saying it
provided the government with stability. But many people that too
much power was concentrated in De Mita's hands.
   Forlani, 64, who was premier in 1980-81, went into the congress
with the support of the party's center faction, believed to control
about one-third of the 1,312 delegates. He also had the backing of
the about 20 percent of the delegates loyal to Foreign Minister
Giulio Andreotti.
   After Forlani's speech, leaders of the party's left wing said
they would not block his candidacy. De Mita was expected to be named
party president, a largely ceremonial post.
   The Christian Democrats have been increasing their vote total in
recent years after nearly being overtaken by the Communist Party in
the early 1980s.
   One De Mita adviser, former Sen. Francesco d'Onofrio, admitted
that Forlani's nomination marked a defeat for the premier. But he
noted ``the positive result of having obliged the new majority to
approve De Mita's political line with a formal motion.''
</TEXT>
