<HEAD>Report: Canadian Senate Likely To Probe Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Canadian Senate likely will conduct its own
investigation of the 1985 crash in Gander, Newfoundland, of a plane
carrying U.S. servicemen, a newspaper reported.
   The report follows calls to reopen a probe that ended in December
with Canadian investigators divided over what caused the crash that
killed 248 soldiers and a crew of eight.
   Herb Gray, deputy leader of the opposition Liberal Party in the
House of Commons, said Wednesday his party wants the Senate to
conduct an inquiry into the crash, Canada's worst aviation disaster.
   ``There are so many lingering doubts and questions that something
more has to be done,'' the Ottawa Citizen quoted Gray as saying late
last week.
   The Arrow Air charter DC-8, carrying soldiers of the 101st
Airborne Division back to Fort Campbell, Ky., from peacekeeping
duties in the Middle East, crashed shortly after takeoff from Gander
airport on Dec. 12, 1985.
   The Canadian Aviation Safety Board concluded Dec. 8 that ice on
the wings was the likely cause, but a minority said in a separate
opinion that an in-flight fire caused the crash.
   Aviation Week and Space Technology, has recently called on the
Canadian government to reopen the inquiry because of unanswered
questions.
