<FIRST>r i AM-Ireland-Ryan     02-19 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ireland-Ryan,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Ex-Priest Sought By Britain Has Left Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Ryan, a former Roman Catholic
priest wanted in Britain on bombing charges, has left the Irish
Republic and is either in France or the United States, The Sunday
Press reported.
   The Dublin weekly said Ryan quietly left the country while legal
authorities were considering whether he should face charges in an
Irish court.
   It said Ryan had left the republic and returned once before since
Belgian authorities in November refused a British request for his
extradition and flew him home on a military aircraft, accompanied by
a prison doctor. The Irish government also refused to extradite him,
saying he would not receive a fair trial in Britain.
   The affair led to an angry exchange between British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher and Belgian Prime Minister Dr. Wilfried
Martens at a European Economic Community summit in December. Irish
Prime Minister Charles Haughey publicly snubbed Mrs. Thatcher there.
   Ryan's attorney, Elio Malocco, would not confirm or deny the
newspaper report but The Sunday Press quoted him as saying he had
not seen his client since Christmas.
   Britain said in its extradition warrant that Ryan conspired to
commit murder and cause explosions in Britain between 1975 and 1988.
He was arrested in a Brussels apartment in June and went on a 22-day
hunger strike to avoid being sent to Britain.
   Although he rejected the British extradition request, Ireland's
Attorney General John Murray asked British authorities for evidence
which might sustain a prosecution in the republic under the criminal
law jurisdiction act. The act allows trial in the republic for
offenses allegedly committed in Britain.
</TEXT>
