<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Stock Prices Move To Record High in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar eased against the Japanese yen while
stock prices moved to a record high at the start of the trading week
Monday.
   The dollar opened at 125.30 yen, down 0.42 yen from last Friday's
close of 125.72 yen. It finished at 125.88 yen in Friday's New York
trading.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said the market remained
relatively quiet because most banks and financial markets in the
United States would be closed Monday for the President's Day holiday.
   The dealer, who spoke anonymously, said the Tokyo market showed
little reaction to a U.S. trade report issued last week which
revealed that the American trade deficit narrowed to $11.89 billion
in December from a revised $12.22 billion the previous month.
   The report was largely within expectations, the dealer said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which rose 89.91 points for a record
32,173.39-point closing Friday, added another 119.16 points, or 0.37
percent, shortly after the market opened to move to 32,292.55.
   The previous high closing was set last Wednesday when the index
finished at 32,149.48 points.
